    {
      "key": "9475b0bd-6a58-4318-b3e5-0d77cfe5a35d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "contentCorner",
            "markdown": "If necessary provide context of some facts about the Internet:\r\n\r\n* The Internet is not inherently secure. \r\n* Packets traveling across the Internet move through many routers, each of which could be owned by different people or organizations.\r\n* So we should *assume* all information traveling across the Internet to be public, as if written on a postcard and sent through the mail. \r\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9475b0bd-6a58-4318-b3e5-0d77cfe5a35d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d42497ec-48f5-404c-90b9-2133dd4759cc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "75673a5f-7781-4876-8d91-9157f53161c2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Secrecy is a critical part of our lives, in ways big and small. As our lives increasingly are conducted on the Internet, we want to be sure we can maintain the privacy of our information and control who has access to privileged information. \r\n\r\nDigital commerce, business, government operations, and even social networks all rely on our ability to keep information from falling into the wrong hands.\r\n\r\nWe need a way to send secret messages...",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "75673a5f-7781-4876-8d91-9157f53161c2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d42497ec-48f5-404c-90b9-2133dd4759cc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "281279d4-2b9b-48f4-b0fa-cb7017a86c91",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Background:**\r\n\r\n*Many of the ideas we use to keep secrets in the digital age are far older than the Internet.  The process of encoding a plain text message in some secret way is called **Encryption*** \r\n\r\n*For example in Roman times Julius Caesar is reported to have encrypted messages to his soldiers and generals by using a simple alphabetic shift - every character was encrypted by substituting it with a character that was some fixed number of letters away in the alphabet.*\r\n\r\n*As a result an alphabetic shift is often referred to as the **Caesar Cipher**.*\r\n\r\n**Prompt:** \r\n\r\n* This message was encrypted using a Caesar Cipher (an \"alphabetic shift\").\r\n* Let's see how long it takes you to **decode this message** (remember it's just a shifting of the alphabet):",
        "name": "Classic Encryption - The Caesar Cipher\r"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "281279d4-2b9b-48f4-b0fa-cb7017a86c91",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d42497ec-48f5-404c-90b9-2133dd4759cc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b4a270c7-538c-4278-a88e-d074a04fafb4",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Resist the urge to give students a tool or device to aid in cracking this message -- that's coming in the next part of the lesson! Part of the point here is that it's possible without tools.  With tools it becomes trivial, as we'll see next.\r\n\r\nIf students are struggling to start here are a few strategy suggestions:\r\n\r\n* Find a small word and try alphabetic shifts until it's clear that it's an English word\r\n* Remember the letters aren't randomly substituted - the alphabet is just shifted.\r\n* Once you have found the amount of shift the rest comes easily. \t\t  \r\n\r\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b4a270c7-538c-4278-a88e-d074a04fafb4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d42497ec-48f5-404c-90b9-2133dd4759cc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9c5bb1fb-a5dc-4857-89fe-b24f3d0ab8bb",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Display or write this on the board*\r\n\r\n```\r\n\tserr cvmmn va gur pnsrgrevn\r\n```    \r\n\r\n* **Give students about 3-5 minutes** to work on cracking the message.\r\n\t* *ANSWER: \"free pizza in the cafeteria\" - the A-Z alphabet is shifted 13 characters.*\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n**Recap:**\r\n\r\n* With this simple encryption technique it only took a few minutes to decode a small message.\r\n* What if the message were longer BUT you had a computational tool to help you?!"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9c5bb1fb-a5dc-4857-89fe-b24f3d0ab8bb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d42497ec-48f5-404c-90b9-2133dd4759cc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "be8fc72a-c35b-403e-9063-5cb6af4c5b28",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "contentCorner",
            "markdown": "If you'd like your students to read a little bit about **Historical Cryptography** and cracking ciphers, check out 'Substitution Ciphers and Frequency Analaysis' in [Blown to Bits, Chapter 5 - Reading](http://www.bitsbook.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/12/chapter5.pdf) pp. 165-169.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
