    {
      "key": "529245c0-b1fc-416b-aee4-77f322d85c58",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this set of activities students will use two different versions of a simple widget in Code Studio to \"crack\" a messages encoded with substitution ciphers, including an alphabetic shift and random substitution.\n\n![](https://code.org/curriculum/docs/csp/code-studio-icon.png) **Transition to Code Studio**: [Encryption Widgets on Code Studio](https://studio.code.org/s/hoc-encryption)"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "529245c0-b1fc-416b-aee4-77f322d85c58",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b93e20e-e9d8-4407-a1a4-83844434c1e0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3e14940a-f236-48f0-bb1b-17cfad462b20",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "* Have students click on the first (of two) encryption tools in Code Studio for this lesson.  It's labeled as the \"Alphabetic Shift Widget\".",
        "name": "Part 1 - Crack a Caesar Cipher\r"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3e14940a-f236-48f0-bb1b-17cfad462b20",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b93e20e-e9d8-4407-a1a4-83844434c1e0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4e04bf40-bae8-413b-a7f9-e62dc83d808e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Don't rush it, but don't linger on cracking caesar ciphers. Presenting and cracking a caesar cipher should go **pretty fast**.\r\n\r\n**The widget** is pretty self-explanatory. Let students figure out how to use it on their own.\r\n\r\nThe goal here is make points about cracking encryption with computational tools, and start to use some common terms.\r\n\r\nYou should move on to cracking random substitution relatively quickly.\r\n\r\n\r\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4e04bf40-bae8-413b-a7f9-e62dc83d808e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b93e20e-e9d8-4407-a1a4-83844434c1e0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "19da6882-e123-46c0-a3e6-d51cdfbfb524",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The instructions for this activity are simple - there is no handout:\r\n\r\n* Put students in pairs/partners\r\n\r\n**Goal:** Select a message encrypted with a caesar cipher and use the provided widget to \"crack\" it. \r\n\r\n* Experiment with the tool - Click things, poke around, figure out what it's doing.\r\n* **Choose one of the messages from the pull down menu and try to crack it** using the tool.\r\n* If you want to, enter you own message, encrypt it, and have a friend decrypt it.\r\n\r\n**Give students about 5 minutes** to get into the tool and crack a few messages\r\n\r\n* Aided with the tool, cracking an alphabetic shift is trivial.\r\n* Once you've done one, it only takes a matter of seconds to do others.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n**Optional - Pause and Recap:**\r\n\r\nThere is a page in Code studio which recaps terminology (encryption, decryption, crack, cipher, Caesar ciper) and poses the next problem.\r\n\r\nYou may optionally pause here to recap and go over terms if you like or just let students proceed (see activity part 2 below)."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "19da6882-e123-46c0-a3e6-d51cdfbfb524",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b93e20e-e9d8-4407-a1a4-83844434c1e0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "41c7a442-e5f1-4440-ad9a-d892d852fa3f",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "After re-capping the first activity make sure **students understand the following before proceeding:**\r\n\r\n* *Cracking a Caesar cipher is easy...trivial with a computational tool like the one we used.*\r\n* *The next step is to make the encryption slightly harder...*\r\n\r\n**New Challenge:**\r\n\r\n* *What if instead of shifting the whole alphabet, we mapped every letter of the alphabet to a random different letter of the alphabet? This is called a **random substitution cipher.***\r\n\r\n* *The **new version of the widget** you'll see is a more sophisticated version of the encryption tool that shows you lots of different stuff.*\r\n\r\n* **But what it does is bit of a mystery!**  Let's check it out...",
        "name": "Part 2 - Crack a Random Substitution Cipher\r"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "41c7a442-e5f1-4440-ad9a-d892d852fa3f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b93e20e-e9d8-4407-a1a4-83844434c1e0"
      }
    },
